  ],
  "activity_sections": [
    {
      "key": "915cad23-79c1-4dcf-87a1-b8f8472ff7de",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": " <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *computer system*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss**: *What are some examples of computing systems you use in everyday life?*\n- Use Think-Pair-Share to facilitate this discussion.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Computer systems are everywhere in daily life, from smartphones and gaming consoles to self-checkout kiosks, smart home devices, and even AI-powered cars. This discussion helps students recognize how these systems process and respond to data in different ways. (e.g. *\"A smartwatch is a computer system because it tracks my steps and syncs data to my phone.\"*)",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students struggle to come up with examples, prompt them with real-world scenarios:\n* *\"Think about something you use daily that connects to the Internet or processes data.\"*\n* *\"Have you used self-checkout at a store? That’s a computer system!\"*"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "915cad23-79c1-4dcf-87a1-b8f8472ff7de",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9498c943-2634-41f7-a84a-30e96cca2105"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c89e69fe-cc7c-47ad-8805-32380d9d370a",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in groups of three.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Computer Innovations and Careers activity guide."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c89e69fe-cc7c-47ad-8805-32380d9d370a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9498c943-2634-41f7-a84a-30e96cca2105"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a123e54d-1438-4957-8bc9-58b83dca4d4a",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Let’s explore how computing drives computing innovation in different industries worldwide. In groups, you'll examine the computing innovation map and choose an innovation to investigate. Be prepared to share your findings!",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a123e54d-1438-4957-8bc9-58b83dca4d4a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9498c943-2634-41f7-a84a-30e96cca2105"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3ef5f00c-f231-41db-8abc-5d5d80432d3e",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 1, Level 1. Students should open the Computer Innovation Map, and click on the markers to explore innovations in medicine, agriculture, education, and fashion. The markers have videos and descriptions to learn about each innovation. Students should select one innovation to investigate, then complete the first page of their activity guide.",
        "progression_name": "Pick an Innovation"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3ef5f00c-f231-41db-8abc-5d5d80432d3e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9498c943-2634-41f7-a84a-30e96cca2105"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "34f63961-730c-4072-93ce-2c2b6a7f439c",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "34f63961-730c-4072-93ce-2c2b6a7f439c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9498c943-2634-41f7-a84a-30e96cca2105"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "67464926-1d4a-4b25-9028-5a2725dcd3fd",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Innovations exist to solve real-world problems for people in different industries. To truly understand your chosen innovation, you’ll interview professionals in that field. Learn about their work, the challenges they face, and how computing helps them. This will help you see why your innovation is important and how it’s making their job easier, faster, or more effective. Remember, innovation starts with people—it’s *their* needs that drive new ideas.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Exploring Innovations",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "67464926-1d4a-4b25-9028-5a2725dcd3fd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f766d4a4-ca3d-46f7-bfca-114563604110"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "94944e8c-06eb-463d-8b6a-ffd89aeb7f6e",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 1, Level 2. Levels 2 through 9 have several industry professionals they can interview in different industries. Student should choose the level that matches their selected innovation and complete the Industry Interviews section of their activity guide.",
        "progression_name": "Industry Interviews"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "94944e8c-06eb-463d-8b6a-ffd89aeb7f6e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f766d4a4-ca3d-46f7-bfca-114563604110"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "28d353a2-d485-4b83-b252-ad3123e62ebc",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "So far, you’ve explored how industry professionals use computing innovations and the challenges they face. Now, let’s shift to the technical roles—the engineers, developers, and designers who build and refine these innovations. These experts work closely with industry professionals to gather feedback, test solutions, and ensure the technology meets real-world needs. Next, you’ll watch career videos to learn about these roles, then conduct an AI interview with a professional to understand their impact on innovation.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Defining Roles and Developing Innovations",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "28d353a2-d485-4b83-b252-ad3123e62ebc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f766d4a4-ca3d-46f7-bfca-114563604110"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "009679d2-a20e-4ad1-bec1-49b576efef45",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students each choose one of the roles (Hardware Engineer, Software Engineer, Product Designer) within their group - each group should have only one person serving that role.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition**: Direct students to Lesson 1, Level 10. Each student selects the option with their assigned technical role. They watch a short video to introduce them to the skills and responsibilities for their selected role.",
        "progression_name": "Exploring Technical Roles"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "009679d2-a20e-4ad1-bec1-49b576efef45",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f766d4a4-ca3d-46f7-bfca-114563604110"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c659f9da-cdf7-480c-87a3-58081f0c6d8e",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Students will share their observations about the career they explored in a whole class discussion.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What stood out to you about the career you explored?*\n- **Round Robin Sharing**: Invite students to share one insight about their chosen career. If time allows, go around the room or ask for volunteers.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** This discussion aims to encourage students to reflect on the skills and tools used in different computing careers and to connect these insights to their own interests. (e.g., *\"I didn’t realize product designers help decide how apps and websites look and feel!\"*).\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition**: Direct students to Lesson 1, Level 11. Student use AI chat to research how their assigned role contributes to building their selected innovation and record their findings on page 3 their activity guide.",
        "progression_name": "Your Role in Innovation"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c659f9da-cdf7-480c-87a3-58081f0c6d8e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f766d4a4-ca3d-46f7-bfca-114563604110"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f46cc8de-97c3-4a2c-99fa-f3d26d2a73de",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** In their groups, students take turns sharing how their role contributes to building their selected innovation and record notes in the Your Role in Innovation section of their activity guide."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f46cc8de-97c3-4a2c-99fa-f3d26d2a73de",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f766d4a4-ca3d-46f7-bfca-114563604110"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "69890191-c8d4-465c-af95-1553e4ef6604",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Pair student groups with another student group (ideally one with a different selected innovation) to share their findings.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 1, Level 12 to complete the reflection questions.",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The reflection questions on Level 12 can be used to assess students' understanding of different career pathways in computing and how computer systems and people work together to solve problems."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "69890191-c8d4-465c-af95-1553e4ef6604",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8c4602ba-171f-4efc-9398-f1ce00754dae"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "17ac40f6-ab62-4eb5-9908-21f81c8314ec",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "17ac40f6-ab62-4eb5-9908-21f81c8314ec",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8c4602ba-171f-4efc-9398-f1ce00754dae"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "278c0aea-077d-44c9-95ab-c9de12199cde",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": " <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Define *hardware*."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "278c0aea-077d-44c9-95ab-c9de12199cde",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fab12dd7-8d11-4123-a39b-e67ba0083f33"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e0b59d5a-0b12-44f2-89a4-c591c4e2429a",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "The most noticeable hardware devices are input and output devices, also known as peripherals.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e0b59d5a-0b12-44f2-89a4-c591c4e2429a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fab12dd7-8d11-4123-a39b-e67ba0083f33"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9132ad5b-72e4-4d4b-9a7e-3e8f9a5674e8",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Define*input devices*and*output devices*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Place students in groups of three.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Hardware activity guide."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9132ad5b-72e4-4d4b-9a7e-3e8f9a5674e8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fab12dd7-8d11-4123-a39b-e67ba0083f33"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8974475b-f028-472e-b180-978d19943cd2",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Input and output devices are all around us—they’re how we interact with and receive information from computer systems every day. Now, let’s take a closer look at the devices in our classroom. In your groups, walk around and observe different devices. For each one, decide if it’s an input device, an output device, or both. Then, record your observations in the Venn diagram in your activity guide.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8974475b-f028-472e-b180-978d19943cd2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fab12dd7-8d11-4123-a39b-e67ba0083f33"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a2829586-1839-48b0-83ec-5cbc793ec33e",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** In their groups, students walk around the classroom, identify different input and output devices, and record their observations in the Venn Diagram in the Device Walk section of their activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Students will discuss the essential components a computer needs to function beyond input and output devices.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:**  *Besides input and output devices, what other components does a computer need to work?*\n- Round Robin Sharing: Invite students to share one insight about a crucial internal component that makes a computer function (e.g., CPU, RAM, storage, power supply). If time allows, go around the room or ask for volunteers.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** This discussion aims to help students recognize that a computer is more than just peripherals—it requires processing power, memory, and storage to operate. By identifying these key components, students will build a foundation for understanding how computers process and store information.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a2829586-1839-48b0-83ec-5cbc793ec33e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fab12dd7-8d11-4123-a39b-e67ba0083f33"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "21383f69-e221-4af8-b2c5-e26e782a72c4",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "So far, we’ve learned about input and output devices—these are the parts of a computer that let us interact with it. But computers do more than just take in and display information. They also need to store dataand process it before sending the results to an output device. All computers, from smartphones to supercomputers, follow a basic cycle called the ISPO Model—which stands for Input, Storage, Process, and Output. Let’s watch a short video that explains these four key components in more detail.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Hardware Components",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "21383f69-e221-4af8-b2c5-e26e782a72c4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c63e32-e5b6-4ebc-9aa5-a4367f230105"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "feb6713d-cdc3-44c0-8abd-099c312a89f5",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the video \"How Computers Work\" from timemarks 2:50 to 4:24 to learn about the ISPO model."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "feb6713d-cdc3-44c0-8abd-099c312a89f5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c63e32-e5b6-4ebc-9aa5-a4367f230105"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ac14b34f-4f15-4ed1-a422-b759cecd2855",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Computers rely on both memory and storage to manage data efficiently. While they might seem similar, they have very different roles in how a computer operates.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ac14b34f-4f15-4ed1-a422-b759cecd2855",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c63e32-e5b6-4ebc-9aa5-a4367f230105"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f4c5760b-355c-4aaa-b5a3-634993e684be",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Define*memory*and*storage*."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f4c5760b-355c-4aaa-b5a3-634993e684be",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c63e32-e5b6-4ebc-9aa5-a4367f230105"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dbf258ee-0f93-462a-8ad4-cf24e686d21a",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Let’s take a look at actual storage and memory components. These components play a crucial role in how a computer accesses and saves information. Everything from opening a file to loading a game depends on memory and storage working together. In this activity, you'll explore these components and create an analogy to explain their roles.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dbf258ee-0f93-462a-8ad4-cf24e686d21a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c63e32-e5b6-4ebc-9aa5-a4367f230105"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d924db78-e82f-4253-9091-1fda1978efe1",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition**: Direct students to Lesson 2, Level 1. Each student will read about storage and memory components and take notes by writing a definition and an analogy for each in the Storage & Memory section of their activity guide.",
        "progression_name": "Storage and Memory Components"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d924db78-e82f-4253-9091-1fda1978efe1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c63e32-e5b6-4ebc-9aa5-a4367f230105"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7a87abac-3c38-4789-938a-a058b3ccfa44",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that we've talked about storage and memory, let's move on to another critical part of a computer—processing components.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7a87abac-3c38-4789-938a-a058b3ccfa44",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c63e32-e5b6-4ebc-9aa5-a4367f230105"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c2163b5f-b9c0-4d39-bb00-caa85c10493d",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Define*processing components*."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c2163b5f-b9c0-4d39-bb00-caa85c10493d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c63e32-e5b6-4ebc-9aa5-a4367f230105"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "187fb476-4905-425c-86a4-816b49a84046",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Everything from opening an app to playing a video game relies on processing power. In this activity, you’ll learn more about these components and create an analogy to explain their role.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "187fb476-4905-425c-86a4-816b49a84046",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c63e32-e5b6-4ebc-9aa5-a4367f230105"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3ef8f0db-30d0-42e5-b902-edf36877ee3b",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition**: Direct students to Lesson 2, Level 2. Each student will read about processing components and take notes by writing a definition and an analogy for each in the Processing Components section of their activity guide.",
        "progression_name": "Processing Components"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3ef8f0db-30d0-42e5-b902-edf36877ee3b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c63e32-e5b6-4ebc-9aa5-a4367f230105"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bd44885c-53aa-46f3-834b-6587ce24bbcc",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that we’ve explored individual computer components, let’s see how they all come together to make a functioning system. In this activity, you’ll be using the PC Builder web app to assemble a computer by dragging and placing each component where it belongs. As you do this, think about how these components interact and depend on one another.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bd44885c-53aa-46f3-834b-6587ce24bbcc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c63e32-e5b6-4ebc-9aa5-a4367f230105"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7d0a0c9a-2fc4-457d-b588-9026feef53f1",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition**: Direct students to Lesson 2, Level 3. Each student will open the PC Builder web app and drag and drop components from the left panel into the diagram, placing them in their correct locations. They will then select a highlight color to categorize each component based on its role in the computer system.",
        "progression_name": "Connecting Components"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7d0a0c9a-2fc4-457d-b588-9026feef53f1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c63e32-e5b6-4ebc-9aa5-a4367f230105"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c18ee2b4-2f3a-4b96-b422-bb93729b0d2e",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that you’ve built a computer, let’s explore how different professionals rely on specific components for their work. Whether it's gaming, music production, content creation, or graphic design, each of these fields depends on certain hardware components to get the best performance. In this next activity, you'll choose a career perspective, watch a video from an expert in that field, and reflect on the role of a key component like the GPU, CPU, SSD, or RAM.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Career Hardware Needs",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c18ee2b4-2f3a-4b96-b422-bb93729b0d2e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c63e32-e5b6-4ebc-9aa5-a4367f230105"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9fc9c339-a585-4966-884f-38365521c02d",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:**  Direct students to Lesson 2, Level 4 to complete Levels 4 and 5. Each student will select a career option—gamer, music producer, content creator, or graphic designer. They will watch a short video where the professional explains how a specific hardware component (GPU, CPU, SSD, or RAM) impacts their work.",
        "progression_name": "Career Hardware Needs",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Use responses to this reflection question to see how well students grasp the importance of different hardware components. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9fc9c339-a585-4966-884f-38365521c02d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c63e32-e5b6-4ebc-9aa5-a4367f230105"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2c2958c5-050b-45f3-9448-dd56af3338a9",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2c2958c5-050b-45f3-9448-dd56af3338a9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c63e32-e5b6-4ebc-9aa5-a4367f230105"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e13a4e0c-03bc-4b61-962f-39ef08e1babe",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the video \"Build My First PC\" from timemarks 1:08 to 5:48 to learn how to assemble a computer from scratch.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Ask students to share their thoughts with the class after watching the “How to Build a PC” video.\n- *What did you notice about the process of building a computer?*\n- *Did anything surprise you?*"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e13a4e0c-03bc-4b61-962f-39ef08e1babe",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6bca7d7f-7a95-4d40-81f1-08c5a8ae07e7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9f46ca71-b8df-4162-8a20-fed88ab124e2",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Guess Who? Device Edition handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students write one to two**yes**or**no**questions with a shoulder partner that can help to narrow down the possible devices (*e.g. Does the device have a touch screen?*)\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Call on students and have them pose one of their questions to ask out loud. You should answer with a***Yes***or***No***depending which device you’ve chosen. Instruct students to cross out the options they think are eliminated based on your answer on their activity guides. Continue this until students the majority of students raise their hand, signaling that are able to use deductive reasoning in order to accurately guess the device.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What strategy did you use to determine the device?*\n- *How could you have arrived at the correct device quicker?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students might have asked about specific properties – the use, the appearance, or the price, for instance. By asking enough of these questions, they are able to systematically eliminate possibilities until only one remains. This is an example of deductive reasoning and is a useful troubleshooting strategy that we will use in today's lesson. Students might note that asking the questions in a different order might have helped them narrow down the potential right answer more quickly depending on which question they asked first. Asking a question that might eliminate the most possible answers is an effective strategy to employ.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9f46ca71-b8df-4162-8a20-fed88ab124e2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8b6d2f27-6ac1-4470-a89e-f54cbeae0e57"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5f1eb948-e070-4c84-96fe-2eaaacef8175",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *troubleshooting*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the SNOT troubleshooting strategy and the first step.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the second step of the SNOT strategy.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the third step of the SNOT strategy.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the last step of the SNOT strategy.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a copy of the Troubleshooting Hardware Issues activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:**  Students should navigate to Lesson 3, Level 1.",
        "name": "Troubleshooting Hardware Issues",
        "progression_name": "Wearable Troubleshooting Scenario"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5f1eb948-e070-4c84-96fe-2eaaacef8175",
        "lesson_activity.key": "46ce91b4-1330-4d28-896e-844b11283109"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9e889b48-0967-41ac-8df7-38e48e8dda39",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Ask a student read the description of the issue in the first panel, then have students examine the diagram on the right-hand side. This diagram is an abstraction of a computing system with descriptions of the important hardware components and connections. Students should restate the issue that the user in their own words under the ***Self*** step on page one of their activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** With a partner, students should examine the possible technical solutions to Maya's issue with her wearable on the second panel of Level 1. Have them select the most likely solutions and write them in the boxes under the ***Neighbor*** portion of their activity guide. Encourage students to also add a few of their own ideas into the activity guide as well.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Students should examine the online resources presented on the remaining panels on Level 1 to narrow down Maya's problem further. In their activity guide, have them cross out solutions that seem unlikely given the new information that they learn from these online resources.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "From these online resources, students should realize that the issue seems to be centered around either the ***power level*** or ***storage capacity***, so they should be able to eliminate options that aren’t related to either of these categories. Model this for students for this scenario if you feel like your students would benefit from understanding how to use deductive reasoning to eliminate options they may have written down on their activity guides. Remind them about how this process is similar to the Guess Who? Warm-up activity."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9e889b48-0967-41ac-8df7-38e48e8dda39",
        "lesson_activity.key": "46ce91b4-1330-4d28-896e-844b11283109"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d2dd8e77-afb9-4d73-bba4-cea75976a283",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d2dd8e77-afb9-4d73-bba4-cea75976a283",
        "lesson_activity.key": "46ce91b4-1330-4d28-896e-844b11283109"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d9fff58a-d09c-4b9a-9196-e31677f71f1c",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We’ve already brainstormed possible reasons why Maya’s fitness tracker isn’t working. Now, let’s use those ideas to ask her questions that help us eliminate incorrect causes and find the real issue! Our goal is to rule out possibilities one by one until we find the most likely cause. In this case, you will be acting as the Technical Expert to assist Maya while an AI will be acting as Maya.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d9fff58a-d09c-4b9a-9196-e31677f71f1c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "46ce91b4-1330-4d28-896e-844b11283109"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ab36f1d2-02b4-4d7f-9efe-9ae423a6b4c3",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Lesson 3, Level 2. Guide students through troubleshooting Maya’s wearable as a class:\n- Use this [**example script**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1EYYl4pCvx9htfz1RpXylU3SZpaUf_K_dlkUNeNPZMmQ/edit?usp=sharing) for the demo.\n- Model how to ask logical questions to gather information and eliminate incorrect causes.\n- Reference the activity guide to pull information from self, a neighbor, and online resources.\n- Show how to use deductive reasoning to propose and test a solution.",
        "progression_name": "Troubleshooting Maya's Wearable"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ab36f1d2-02b4-4d7f-9efe-9ae423a6b4c3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "46ce91b4-1330-4d28-896e-844b11283109"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b0554cac-6705-46d3-a88d-0853f3b2b72b",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Lesson 3, Level 3 to complete the **You Do** section of the activity guide.",
        "progression_name": "Hardware Troubleshooting Scenarios"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b0554cac-6705-46d3-a88d-0853f3b2b72b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "46ce91b4-1330-4d28-896e-844b11283109"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b1371453-be5a-4380-89f5-e57c9abaf8cb",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Assist students as necessary with the steps of the SNOT strategy."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b1371453-be5a-4380-89f5-e57c9abaf8cb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "46ce91b4-1330-4d28-896e-844b11283109"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7f666f87-cc93-49e2-9bab-29e0ab33e327",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Next, you will assume the role of the technical expert, acting like an IT support agent. Ask questions, investigate potential causes, and use available resources to find the most logical solution.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7f666f87-cc93-49e2-9bab-29e0ab33e327",
        "lesson_activity.key": "46ce91b4-1330-4d28-896e-844b11283109"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "92aff9a2-eaf7-4117-bfe7-b10be7a1e11a",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Direct students to Lesson 3, Level 4. Students act as tech support for a user experiencing the same issue in the AI Chatbot simulation. They should complete their activity guide for the scenario that they have chosen, identifying the most likely cause of the problem.",
        "progression_name": "Tech Support Chatbot"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "92aff9a2-eaf7-4117-bfe7-b10be7a1e11a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "46ce91b4-1330-4d28-896e-844b11283109"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d2f4e156-5caa-408a-a661-979816e45dbc",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How did employing a strategy for troubleshooting assist with resolving hardware issues?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students might articulate that using a strategy like SNOT reduces guesswork and frustration by breaking down the problem into manageable parts (**decomposition***in computational thinking*), helps pinpoint causes more quickly and accurately, and encourages independent, logical problem-solving skills that transfer to various real-world situations.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define*decomposition*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 3, Level 5 to complete Levels 5 and 6.\n- **Level 5:** Students choose one of the videos that provides details about a hardware-related career\n- **Level 6:** Students speculate about how troubleshooting strategies might be employed within this specific career",
        "progression_name": "Hardware Careers: Components and Troubleshooting"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d2f4e156-5caa-408a-a661-979816e45dbc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "46ce91b4-1330-4d28-896e-844b11283109"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6f473594-731a-47b6-b368-016befeededd",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6f473594-731a-47b6-b368-016befeededd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "46ce91b4-1330-4d28-896e-844b11283109"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "954ac5ed-ef37-46d3-b046-0067e25c18ae",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What real-life problems could benefit from a troubleshooting strategy and how?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students share examples of problems they have encountered before where the troubleshooting strategy they used today could have helped them.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "954ac5ed-ef37-46d3-b046-0067e25c18ae",
        "lesson_activity.key": "95a6a934-f1f9-43de-8c27-fd3f12327a29"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f3d81911-5bc6-4f17-ac44-9f39db1cc288",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Let’s review some of the major points from our last few lessons about hardware and software. Software is like the set of instructions that tells a computer what to do. It’s the code and programs that make a computer useful. Without software, your computer, phone, or tablet would just be a box of wires and circuits—it wouldn’t know how to do anything. Software and hardware are like a team. The hardware performs the physical tasks—like displaying images on the screen, printing a document, or saving files on a hard drive. But it’s the software that decides*what*to display, print, or save and*how* to do it.\u000bFor example, if you press a key on a keyboard, the hardware sends the signal to the operating system (a type of software), which decides what letter to show on the screen. When you swipe through TikTok, the hardware detects your touch, and the app software loads the next video.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f3d81911-5bc6-4f17-ac44-9f39db1cc288",
        "lesson_activity.key": "dc174765-fc1e-4b64-95ef-0cbfb4fffeac"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c0ddaaba-d519-41dd-b5c9-2b1e81bcdff6",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Click through the animated slide to show each scenario and ask students which device they would use for that scenario. Ask students to hold up one finger if they would choose laptop, two fingers if they would choose a phone, or three fingers for a tablet. Have students look around the room to see if their answer is different from their peers. Call on a student after each prompt to justify their answer.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c0ddaaba-d519-41dd-b5c9-2b1e81bcdff6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "dc174765-fc1e-4b64-95ef-0cbfb4fffeac"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2dedb2dd-e898-4534-be97-d613f3377f1a",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:**  Show the video \"How Computers Work: Hardware and Software\"\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Questions To Consider with the **Video:** \n- *What pieces of hardware do you recognize?*\n- *How are operating systems different from other types of software?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize the CPU and also various input and output components in the video. They may also point out that in the video “Memory” has a generic label but that this job would be taken care of by a hard drive or RAM. Listen for students to rephrase “master program” from the video in their own words or articulate that it controls which software runs and which input and output devices it has access to.",
        "name": "Software Scavenger Hunt",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "To encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Y-kGl_pc2afuSBKhKkdulu53X50mc7T-RQZA4vGLpY4/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2dedb2dd-e898-4534-be97-d613f3377f1a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a8868a21-1a73-4fda-a988-c89e910be198"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "166addb0-1014-4628-90cd-55c79be60550",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "166addb0-1014-4628-90cd-55c79be60550",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a8868a21-1a73-4fda-a988-c89e910be198"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4cb71192-e7a0-4f47-9aba-c970e8c20ac5",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Software and hardware are like a team. The hardware performs the physical tasks—like displaying images on the screen, printing a document, or saving files on a hard drive. But it’s the software that decides what to display, print, or save and how to do it.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4cb71192-e7a0-4f47-9aba-c970e8c20ac5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a8868a21-1a73-4fda-a988-c89e910be198"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "27080514-4c97-4164-9139-cc8f263c8883",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the components of a computer system diagram.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Click through the animated slide to introduce operating systems, application software, and utility software.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Have each pair make a copy of the Scavenger Hunt slides.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Have students work on the Scavenger Hunt.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students are working encourage them to share task solutions with each other as they explore where to find these. Push them to consider looking in multiple places and on different devices for the tasks they might get stuck on. They don’t need to find all the solutions on a single device or platform. If students finish early, push them to find as many examples for the bonus tasks as possible.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 4, Level 1 to answer the questions.",
        "progression_name": "Software Scavenger Hunt Debrief",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This level is designed to use the Student Summaries feature, which lets you view and display the responses from the class. This requires having this level opened on your computer and, in the teacher panel, selecting the current section of your classes. [**Click here to learn more about viewing student responses**](https://support.code.org/hc/en-us/articles/14544890300301-Can-I-see-a-summary-of-all-my-students-responses-for-question-based-levels). If you are unable to use the student summaries, you can also run this as an unplugged discussion where students vote in their seats or move to different corners of the room depending on their responses. Ultimately, students need a way to take a stand and be ready to discuss their opinions in the next slide."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "27080514-4c97-4164-9139-cc8f263c8883",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a8868a21-1a73-4fda-a988-c89e910be198"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "506322ae-556e-44e3-a52f-18e49410a0ae",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "506322ae-556e-44e3-a52f-18e49410a0ae",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a8868a21-1a73-4fda-a988-c89e910be198"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "98dd11d7-28d4-43e9-8367-27640e06c4c7",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What did you learn about the roles of operating systems, application software, and utility software?*\n- *Which of these types of software do you use most often, and why?*\n- *How do you think understanding these tools will help you in the future?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Ensure students can clearly articulate the distinct roles of each type of software: operating systems manage hardware and software, application software helps users complete tasks, and utility software keeps systems running smoothly. Help students connect the lesson to their own lives by identifying the software they use regularly. Highlight how each type of software impacts their day-to-day activities, such as gaming, communicating, or studying. Prompt students to consider why some types of software might feel more \"invisible\" (like utility software) compared to application software they interact with directly. Discuss how knowledge of these software types applies to future careers or problem-solving scenarios (e.g., using applications in a job, troubleshooting operating systems, optimizing devices with utilities). Emphasize how understanding software roles can make students more independent when troubleshooting or choosing the right tools for a task. Help students see the value of learning about software now to prepare for challenges in technology-driven fields or daily life."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "98dd11d7-28d4-43e9-8367-27640e06c4c7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a8868a21-1a73-4fda-a988-c89e910be198"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2a41510e-152a-480b-a0be-3d25facb20b2",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2a41510e-152a-480b-a0be-3d25facb20b2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a8868a21-1a73-4fda-a988-c89e910be198"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fbf319c0-96ca-4e16-a5b0-fa882a11de1c",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What role does software play in enabling computer systems to function? Give a specific example from today's activities.*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Help students articulate that software enables hardware to perform meaningful tasks and makes devices useful. Emphasize the interdependence of hardware and software in modern technology. Ensure students can link specific examples from the scavenger hunt to their everyday lives or future careers (e.g., writing programs for authors, productivity tools for entrepreneurs, system maintenance tools for IT professionals). Encourage students to consider how their own devices and software enable their daily tasks and what they would do if these systems failed."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fbf319c0-96ca-4e16-a5b0-fa882a11de1c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0fefc3f2-7ed3-489d-a9a5-1e5c5c9058a4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2823f5be-d0e9-49f2-bd69-09834cab5066",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What do these jobs have in common?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Pull out that they all work on seeing how products work, meet certain standards, or don’t.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:**  Show the video \"Meet Test Engineers at Google\"\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Question to Consider While Watching:**\n- *Why do you think Google invests the money and resources that it does into test engineering?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Listen for students to point out that catching errors and bugs will result in a better experience for users and Google’s ability to sell more products. Students may also bring up that companies can build trust in their products by investing money into testing them internally before releasing them to the public.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "To encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Y-kGl_pc2afuSBKhKkdulu53X50mc7T-RQZA4vGLpY4/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2823f5be-d0e9-49f2-bd69-09834cab5066",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b47a161b-512e-41aa-9137-ecd18ed38994"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "36311d97-d34f-4713-8f6b-bfb624ce7cb9",
      "position": 2,
